doc.after: Between the 8th and 11th centuries, raiders and colonists from Scandinavia, mainly Danish and Norwegian, plundered western Europe, including the British Isles.[78] These raiders came to be known as the Vikings; the name is believed to derive from Scandinavia, where the Vikings originated.[79][80] The first raids in the British Isles were in the late 8th century, mainly on churches and monasteries (which were seen as centres of wealth).[79][81] The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle reports that the holy island of Lindisfarne was sacked in 793.[82] The raiding then virtually stopped for around forty years; but in about 835 it started becoming more regular.[83]
